<br>
May 15, 2002 <br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.planetary.org/html/news/articlearchive/headlines/2002/FreemanDyson.htm">Source.</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
&quot;Planets may not be the best places to look for life. They are a good place for life to originate, but not stay.&quot; <br>
To the uninformed, that proposition may sound preposterous -- and if it had come from anyone other than renowned theoretical physicist Freeman Dyson, of the Institute for Advanced Studies at Princeton University, it may well be have been summarily dismissed even in the scientific community. But Dyson has been positing possibilities about extraterrestrial life for more than 50 years and through the decades has earned a reputation for thinking 'out-of-the-box' and putting forth far-reaching, futuristic concepts.<br>
<br>
A longtime friend of The Planetary Society, Dyson dropped by the organization's headquarters in Pasadena, California last week to have lunch, talk about his latest extraterrestrial search ideas, and to get an update on Cosmos 1, the Society's solar sail project from Louis Friedman before the Society's Executive Director took off to Moscow for more meetings on the solar sail, and to observe progress in the testing program for the spacecraft. <br>
<br>
Dyson had traveled from the East Coast to California last week to present his latest concept in the search for extraterrestrial life -- &quot;pit-lamping,&quot; as he calls it -- to a group of scientists and engineers at JPL.<br>
<br>
Pit-lamping <br>
<br>
Adapting the appellation &quot;pit-lamping&quot; from the Canadian term for night-time hunting with a &quot;carefully shielded&quot; flashlight, Dyson contends that this approach is not only highly effective, relatively simple and affordable, it is do-able. &quot;The reason it is so effective is that the eyes of animals staring into the light act as efficient reflectors,&quot; he explains. &quot;The eye reflects a fraction of the light that is focused onto the retina, and the reflected light is again focused into a narrow beam pointing back to the flashlight. If you are standing behind the flashlight, you can see the eyes as bright red points even when the rest of the animal is invisible.&quot;<br>
<br>
Extrapolating along those lines, he says that in order for any lifeform to keep warm using the light from a distant Sun, it &quot;must grow a system of optical concentrators, lenses or mirrors to focus Sunlight onto its vital parts.&quot; It's really not such a far out idea. Some Arctic plants on Earth, he points out, have already evolved something similar, &quot;with parabolic petals reflecting sunlight onto the ovaries and seeds that grow at the center of the flower.&quot;<br>
<br>
Dyson suggests that his pit-lamping method could be used either with space-based telescopes on planetary orbiters - orbital pit-lamping or with ground-based telescopes and telescopes in near-Earth orbit for what he dubs home-based pit-lamping. &quot;To search for such life-forms, we should scan the sky with optical and infra-red telescopes pointing directly away from the Sun,&quot; he expounds. &quot;Any living vegetation will be seen as a bright patch in strong contrast to its dark surroundings, like the eyes of a nocturnal animal caught in the headlights of a car.&quot; Pit-lamping would work well, he says, on the surfaces of Europa, Trojan asteroids, or Kuiper Belt objects. <br>
<br>
The real beauty of the pit-lamping strategy, Dyson says, is that it &quot;becomes more effective the further out you go.&quot; Home-based pit-lamping - which can be carried out from orbiting telescopes like Hubble close to Earth or big telescopes on the ground is another &quot;promising and cost-effective&quot; way to search for life beyond Europa. &quot;When we do home-based pit-lamping, we make a big jump in the distance and the number of objects that we might hope to search,&quot; Dyson says. &quot;Think of the Kuiper Belt, which begins about 10 times further from the Sun than Europa and is supposed to contain billions of objects of size, ranging from a kilometer upward. Suppose that life has somehow succeeded in establishing itself on the surface of one of these objects,&quot; he muses. &quot;This may seem unlikely, but nobody can prove it to be impossible.&quot;<br>
<br>
On terra firma, pit-lamping is so effective, it is illegal, at least in Canada. &quot;Since our purpose is not to kill and eat the creatures but only to discover them, there is no reason why pit-lamping on Europa {or in any other parts of the solar system for that matter} should be illegal,&quot; Dyson says with a smile.<br>
<br>
Detectability Before Probability<br>
<br>
In choosing a strategy to look for life, Dyson emphasizes, &quot;detectability is more important than probability.&quot; The reason is logical enough. &quot;Estimates of the probability of life existing in various places are grossly unreliable but estimate of detectability are generally quite reliable,&quot; he says. &quot;For all we know, all kinds of things might be out there, and we have a chance to find them only if they are detectable.&quot; <br>
<br>
Since orbital and home-based pit-lamping each serves a distinct purpose, neither one is a substitute for the other, Dyson clarifies. &quot;Both are needed if we are to extend our search for life as widely as possible,&quot; he says. While orbital pit-lamping can search for &quot;small and sparse patches of life&quot; on a few objects such as Europa, home-based pit-lamping can scan for &quot;big and luxuriant patches of life&quot; covering the surface of a big number of more distant objects. Orbital pit-lamping on Europa, for example, &quot;is like searching for lichens in rocks in Antarctica with a hand-held magnifying glass,&quot; he says, with home-based pit-lamping in the Kuiper Belt being more &quot;like searching for rain-forests on Earth with a camera on the Moon.&quot;<br>
<br>
As robust a search method as pit-lamping may be, it does have its limits. &quot;We can easily detect any community that uses 100 megawatts of sunlight or more for its life-support, out to a distance of a light-year from the Sun,&quot; Dyson says. Beyond a light-year, however, the Sun is outshone by Sirius. &quot;Anything living beyond a light-year from the Sun would point its concentrators at Sirius rather than at the Sun. At that point, home-based pit-lamping no longer works, unless we are thinking of alien pit-lamping astronomers in orbit around Sirius, with Sirius as their home base.&quot;<br>
<br>
Life in a vacuum<br>
<br>
Dyson also offered up his thoughts on the &quot;possible history and evolution of life&quot; that might exist away from planets during his talk at JPL. In essence, he suggests that if life has emerged and thrived in the vacuum of space, it may be much hardier in many ways than air-breathing life and more adept at colonizing solar systems and galaxies.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.planetary.org/html/Images/Dyson/Burke_Dyson_Friedman.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
Freeman Dyson (center), in intense conversation with Jim Burke (left) and Louis Friedman (right) during his visit to The Planetary Society.<br>
<br>
The two &quot;outstanding qualities&quot; that distinguish living from non-living objects on Earth, Dyson proffers, are adaptability and invasiveness. &quot;During the four billion years that life has existed on Earth, it has adapted itself to an amazing variety of ecological niches . . . from frozen rocks in Antarctica to thermal vents in the depths of the oceans. It is reasonable to expect that life, if it exists elsewhere, will still be characterized by extreme adaptability and invasiveness. In an unstable and unpredictable universe,&quot; he concludes, &quot;these qualities are needed if life is to survive, either on a planet or anywhere else.&quot; <br>
<br>
The concept of vacuum life may seem a bit far-reaching for some, but Dyson points out, Any life-form that has managed to adapt successfully to a vacuum environment, would be &quot;likely to spread widely over objects with icy surfaces in the outer regions of the solar system,&quot; he maintains. &quot;If a chunk of ice is knocked off Europa by a cometary impact, and if the chunk has vacuum-life on its surface, then the life has a good chance to survive the impact and continue to flourish while the chunk wanders around the solar system. The environment after the impact is not much different from the environment before. And if the chunk happens to land on another object with not too high a relative velocity, the life has a chance to survive the second impact and establish itself on another world,&quot; he surmises.<br>
<br>
&quot;Gentle collisions between neighboring objects will be common,&quot; Dyson continues. &quot;Life has a good chance to survive when a gentle collision knocks a piece of its home into space, and when the piece later makes a gentle collision to land on another object. In this way, life could spread from world to world like neutrons in a divergent nuclear chain reaction. A large fraction of the objects in the Kuiper Belt might become inhabited. If this should happen, the process of Darwinian evolution would then select life-forms that are particularly well adapted to traveling. . . Such life-forms would be winners in the race to colonize new worlds. Lifeforms that do not hop, but grow far out into space around their home territory, would also have an advantage in spreading to other worlds.&quot;<br>
<br>
In any case, it would be far easier for vacuum life to spread from one world to another than for air-breathing life, Dyson says, and hopping from world to world would actually become &quot;rapidly easier&quot; as one moves out beyond Jupiter to the Kuiper Belt and the Oort Cloud.<br>
<br>
That is precisely why, Dyson says that planets may not be the best place to look for other life. &quot;Life adapted to a vacuum has the potential to spread from its place of origin, not only from world to world within our solar system, but far and wide through the galaxy,&quot; he reiterates. &quot;Life adapted to an atmosphere is stuck on the planet where it started.&quot;<br>
<br>
The basic problem with planets, Dyson posits, is that they have too little area and too much mass. &quot;Life needs area, not only to collect incident energy but also to dispose of waste heat,&quot; he explains. &quot;In the long run, life will spread to the places where mass can be used most efficiently, far away from planets, to comet clouds or to dust-clouds not too far from a friendly star. If the friendly star happens to be our Sun, we have a chance to detect any wandering life-form that may have settled here,&quot; he says.<br>
<br>
As far-thinking and optimistic as Dyson is about the pit-lamping search approach, he is well aware of the influence of the politics of space missions and the need for solidarity in goals.<br>
<br>
&quot;We may hope to find life with searches targeted on planets and their satellites, on Mars and Europa in particular, but we may have a better chance to find evidence for life in unexpected places if we search in all directions with an all-sky survey,&quot; Dyson sums up. &quot;I will not be surprised if the first extraterrestrial life to be discovered turns up in a part of the sky where there is nothing to be seen but a couple of dim Kuiper Belt objects with anomalously small parallaxes and anomalously slow proper motions. I will also not be surprised if the first sign of life is an anomalous infrared emission from something that looks like a small interstellar dust-cloud,&quot; he adds.<br>
<br>
&quot;Keep on looking for life in unexpected places,&quot; Dyson encourages, &quot;and especially in places where we may find clues to other scientific mysteries that have nothing to do with life.&quot;<br>
